"Should You Include Every Job on Your Resume? Let’s Explore Both Sides.\n\nIs it really necessary to list every single job you’ve ever had on your resume? Let’s break it down.\n\n\nOn one hand, including all your job roles can highlight the breadth of your experience. It shows your career journey, reflects your work ethic, and provides recruiters with a holistic view of your professional history. If you’ve worn many hats over the years, it can even illustrate your adaptability and versatility.\n\n\nOn the other hand, less is often more when it comes to resumes. Omitting roles that don’t align with the job you’re targeting allows you to focus on relevant skills and achievements. A streamlined resume not only keeps things concise but also ensures recruiters quickly spot what makes you a strong fit for the role.\n\n\nSo, how do you structure your resume? Do you prefer to showcase the full spectrum of your work history, or do you tailor it for specific opportunities? Your insights might inspire others in their job search!\n\n\n…more"
"The most common resume mistake I see when working with people:\n\nIncluding a measurable result\n\n... that you literally can't measure.\n\nChatGPT does a great job pulling measurable results to put in your resume when you type in this prompt:\n\n""What are some measurable accomplishments JOB POSITION can put in their resume?""\n\nBut it'll give you ideas that are clearly ChatGPT'd.\n\n""Improved time from order to serving food by 25%""\n\nDid you really time every order and calculate how much your ""tailored customer service strategy reduced xyz""?\n\n...and was it really exactly a 25% increase?\n\nMake sure you pick results that are measurable & more importantly TRUE\n\nYou can fully expect the interviewer to press you on ""how exactly did you achieve this result?""\n\n\n\nCheck comments for a free resume review (only taking on 5 more) 👇\n…more"
