"When a U.S. company wants to hire someone from another country for a technical job, they must apply for a visa or green card for that person. This helps the government keep track of who is coming to work in the U.S. and ensures fair pay and treatment for both U.S. and foreign workers.\n\nAs part of the process, companies must report how much they will pay the new employee and the average salary for similar jobs (called the prevailing wage). Since this information is public, it gives a clear picture of salary trends for data jobs across the U.S.\n\nSo, where do data professionals thrive the most? In my current project I decided to find out.\n\nTo start with, I've created an interactive U.S. heat map that allows to explore median annual pay for various data positions across different states. You can filter by year and specific roles such as data analyst, data scientist, data engineer and even compare with roles like teachers and professors. Hover over a state, and you’ll see salary details based on foreign applicants who filed for permanent residency.\n\n\n\nQuick Findings for Data Scientists (2016–2024): Highest median salaries go to California – $151,500, New York – $145,000 and Washington – $137,000. Lowest median salaries are in Kansas – $87,100, South Dakota – $91,800 and Indiana – $93,000. While higher salaries sound nice, they often come with higher living costs—something I’ll explore in future posts.\n\nOn a journey to find my own data job, I'm excited to share more insights from this project in the coming weeks and would love to hear your thoughts and questions. Anything specific you’d like me to analyze? Looking forward to discussion!\n\n…more"
